# 🧠 What is Cache Eviction?

Cache memory is limited, so when it becomes full, the system must remove some old items to make space for new ones.
The rule used to decide **which item to remove** is called a cache eviction strategy.

📌 Example:
Cache size = 3 and contains A, B, C.
New item D arrives → one item must be removed first.

# 🎯 Why Eviction Strategy Matters

A good eviction policy keeps useful data in cache and removes less useful data.
This improves cache hit rate, response speed, and reduces database load.

📌 Example:
If frequently used product data stays in cache, users get faster responses.

# 🔁 1. LRU (Least Recently Used)

LRU removes the item that has **not been used for the longest time**.
It assumes recently used items are more likely to be used again soon.

📌 Example:
Cache = [A, B, C]
Access A → A becomes recent
Add D → B removed because B was least recently used

✅ Great for web apps and APIs
❌ Needs tracking of access order

# 🔢 2. LFU (Least Frequently Used)

LFU removes the item with the **lowest usage count**.
It assumes rarely used items are less important than popular ones.

📌 Example:
A(5 uses), B(1 use), C(3 uses)
Add D → B removed because lowest frequency

✅ Good for hot/popular content
❌ Needs counters and more memory

# 📦 3. FIFO (First In First Out)

FIFO removes the item that entered cache first, regardless of usage.
It is simple and predictable but ignores access behavior.

📌 Example:
Cache = [A, B, C]
Add D → A removed because A entered first

✅ Very simple
❌ May remove still-useful data

# 🎲 4. Random Replacement (RR)

Random replacement removes any random item when cache is full.
It uses almost no metadata and is easy to implement.

📌 Example:
Cache = [A, B, C]
Add D → randomly B removed

✅ Low overhead
❌ Can remove important frequently used item

# 🔄 5. MRU (Most Recently Used)

MRU removes the **most recently used** item first.
It assumes recently used data may not be needed again immediately.

📌 Example:
Cache = [A, B, C]
Access C
Add D → C removed

✅ Useful in some scanning workloads
❌ Rarely good for normal apps

# ⌛ 6. TTL (Time To Live)

Each cached item gets an expiry time.
Once time is over, the item is automatically removed even if space exists.

📌 Example:
User profile cached for 10 minutes
After 10 mins → removed automatically

✅ Prevents stale data
❌ Popular item may expire too early

# 🏗️ 7. Two-Tiered Caching

Uses two cache layers: local fast cache + remote shared cache.
If local misses, system checks remote cache before database.

📌 Example:
App memory cache miss → Redis hit → no DB query needed

✅ Very fast + scalable
❌ More complex consistency handling

# ⚔️ Quick Comparison

| Strategy | Removes               |
| -------- | --------------------- |
| LRU      | Least recently used   |
| LFU      | Least frequently used |
| FIFO     | Oldest inserted       |
| RR       | Random item           |
| MRU      | Most recently used    |
| TTL      | Expired item          |
| Two-Tier | Uses layered caches   |

# 🧠 Which One to Use?

LRU is most common for general applications.
LFU is strong for stable popular content.
TTL is best when freshness matters.
Two-tier caching is best for large distributed systems.

📌 Example:
News website → TTL
E-commerce → LRU
Streaming platform → Two-tier

# ⚠️ Common Trade-offs

Smart strategies improve hit rate but need extra tracking.
Simple strategies are fast but may make worse eviction choices.

📌 Example:
LRU better than FIFO usually, but uses more metadata.

# 🏁 Final Takeaway

Cache eviction strategy decides how efficiently limited memory is used.
Choosing the right one can dramatically improve performance and reduce backend load.

